title="Algebra">Algebra</fr:link> Exercise 9(b) in Section III.2 asks the reader to prove: if <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[D]]></fr:tex> is a division ring and <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[R=\mathop {\mathrm {Mat}}\nolimits _{n}(D)]]></fr:tex>, then <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[R]]></fr:tex> has zero divisors and so the trivial ideal <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[(0)]]></fr:tex> is prime, which means <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[R\cong  R/(0)]]></fr:tex> but <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[R]]></fr:tex> is not an integral domain. This is because <fr:tex
